Wash and dry all produce. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @red onion{1}. Core, deseed, and dice @poblano pepper{1} into ½-inch pieces. Drain @black beans{1%13.4oz can} over a small #bowl{}, reserving liquid. Finely dice @roma tomato{1}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}. Halve @lime{1}. In a separate small bowl, combine tomato, scallions, a large squeeze of lime juice, and a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tbsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add poblano and onion; cook until just softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add @Southwest spice blend{1%tbsp} and half the beans. Cook, stirring, until fragrant and warmed through, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Remove pan from heat.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tbsp} in a small #pot{} over medium-high heat. Add remaining beans and cook, stirring, until slightly softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add ¼ cup reserved bean liquid (½ cup for 4 servings). Let simmer until warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}. Reduce heat to low and stir in @butter{1%tbsp}. Remove pot from heat, then mash beans with a #potato masher{} or fork until mostly smooth. Season with plenty of salt and pepper.

Spread @flour tortillas{6} with mashed beans. Place a small amount of filling on one half of each tortilla, then sprinkle with @pepper jack cheese{1/2%cup}(diced). Roll up tortillas, starting with filled side, and place seam sides down on a #plate{}.

Wash out pan used for filling. Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%tbsp} in same pan over medium-high heat. Place flautas seam sides down in pan. Cook, carefully turning so they stay intact, until golden brown and crispy, ~{1-2%minutes} per side.

> Work in batches if necessary and watch carefully to avoid burning.

Divide flautas between plates and top with @guacamole{}, @pico de gallo{}, @sour cream{4}, and @hot sauce{1}. Alternatively, serve with toppings on the side for dipping.